The paper presents a new Byzantine consensus algorithm for consortium blockchains, which involves distributed computing, cryptography, and system design. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The paper also deals with security and trust issues, which are relevant to the category cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The algorithm relies on binary consensus, which is a fundamental problem in computer science, and involves data structures and algorithms, which are relevant to the category cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also presents a new approach to consensus validity, which involves logic and reasoning, and could be relevant to the category cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper deals with system optimization and efficiency, which are relevant to the category cs.SY (Systems and Control).
